      • getUpdateSpeedFactor

        public double getUpdateSpeedFactor()
        Gets the speed factor that is applied to all velocity and movement updates in the current update.

        Explanation:
        When a train moves faster than 0.4 blocks/tick, the update is split into several update steps per tick. This prevents nasty derailing and makes sure that block-by-block motion can still occur. In a single tick the train moves 5 blocks, which is done by doing 8 or so actual update steps. The update speed factor specifies the multiplier to apply to speeds for the current update.

        When moving 0.4 b/t and under, this value will always be 1.0 (one update). Above it, it will be set to an increasingly small number 1/stepcount. Outside of the physics function, the factor will always be 1.0.

        When to use
        This factor should only be used when applying an absolute velocity. For example, when a launcher sign uses a certain desired velocity, this speed factor must be used to make sure it is correctly applied. Say we want a speed of "2.4", and the update is split in 6 (f=0.1666), we should apply 2.4*0.1666=0.4. When all updates finish, the velocities are corrected and will be set to the 2.4 that was requested.

        However, when a velocity is taken over from inside the physics loop, this factor should not be used. For example, if you want to do velocity = velocity * 0.95 the original velocity is already factored, and no update speed factor should be applied again.
        Returns:
        Update speed factor
